    "what_description": "Souroubea lepidota is an evergreen shrub or small tree native to the tropical rainforests of Central and South America. It belongs to the family Marcgraviaceae, a group of flowering plants characterized by their unique pollination mechanism involving a sticky droplet of nectar on the anther. Souroubea lepidota features elliptical to lanceolate leaves, 10-30 cm long and 3-8 cm wide, with a leathery texture and a pointed tip. The plant produces white, fragrant flowers, 5-7 cm in diameter, with a five-lobed calyx and a corolla with five petals. The flowers are followed by red, berry-like fruits, 2-3 cm in diameter, containing several seeds.",
