    "intro": "Souroubea lepidota is a species of flowering plant in the family Marcgraviaceae, native to the tropical regions of Central and South America. The plant has been traditionally used for its medicinal properties, including its anti-inflammatory, antimicrobial, and antiseptic properties, which can help to alleviate symptoms of respiratory infections, wounds, and skin conditions. Bioactive constituents of Souroubea lepidota include flavonoids, alkaloids, and phenolic compounds, which have been shown to exhibit antioxidant and immunomodulatory activities. In herbal medicine, Souroubea lepidota is commonly prepared as a tea or tincture, and is used to treat conditions such as fever, cough, and skin irritations."
